l2_implementation_plan.md
Summary
This document is the step-by-step implementation plan for building l2_cache by reusing the current l1_cache structure.

The simplest path is:

Copy the overall structure of l1_cache
Replace the L1-specific request path with L1-to-L2 physical-address interfaces
Add the memory-side request/response interfaces
Expand MSHRs from 2 to 4
Replace 2-way LRU with 4-way n^2 LRU
Verify connectivity first
Verify replacement and writeback behavior after connectivity is stable
The first goal is not a perfect spec-complete L2. The first goal is a working L2 that:

accepts L1 miss requests
accepts L1 writebacks
returns lines back to L1 on L2 hit or after memory fill
writes dirty evictions back to memory
tracks up to 4 misses using MSHRs
uses a correct 4-way replacement policy
How L2 Fits Into the System
What L2 receives
L2 sits below L1 and above memory.

It receives two kinds of traffic from L1:

L1 miss request

L1 sends the physical block address it wants
This is like L1's current l2_req_valid / l2_req_paddr
L1 writeback

L1 sends a full dirty block that it is evicting
This is like L1's current l2_wb_valid / l2_wb_paddr / l2_wb_data
What L2 sends back
L2 sends:

a returned block to L1 for load misses
an ack for L1 writebacks
memory requests downward
memory writeback data downward
Timing model
Use the same style as current L1:

requests are sampled on clock edges
outputs are driven from registered/cache state
fill responses are matched by address
the cache can hold outstanding misses in MSHRs
do not try to model exact 5-cycle L2 latency in v1
first make the protocol correct, then add fixed latency later if needed
External Interface to Build First
Use the current memsys.sv split-wire style.

L1 -> L2 interface
input  logic                    l1_wb_valid,
input  logic [PA_WIDTH-1:0]     l1_wb_paddr,
input  logic [BLOCK_SIZE*8-1:0] l1_wb_data,
output logic                    l1_wb_ack,

input  logic                    l1_req_valid,
input  logic [PA_WIDTH-1:0]     l1_req_paddr,
L2 -> L1 interface
output logic                    l1_data_valid,
output logic [PA_WIDTH-1:0]     l1_data_paddr,
output logic [BLOCK_SIZE*8-1:0] l1_data,
L2 -> Memory interface
output logic                    mem_req_valid,
output logic                    mem_req_is_write,
output logic [PA_WIDTH-1:0]     mem_req_addr,
output logic [BLOCK_SIZE*8-1:0] mem_req_wdata,
input  logic                    mem_req_ready,
Memory -> L2 interface
Use address-tagged responses so L2 can match fills to 4 MSHRs.

input  logic                    mem_resp_valid,
input  logic [PA_WIDTH-1:0]     mem_resp_paddr,
input  logic [BLOCK_SIZE*8-1:0] mem_resp_rdata,
Why mem_resp_paddr matters
L1 currently matches returning blocks by address. L2 should do the same.

Without mem_resp_paddr, once L2 has 4 MSHRs it cannot safely know which response belongs to which miss unless memory is artificially limited to exactly one in-flight read. That makes the design more fragile. Matching by address is the cleanest first implementation.

Step-by-Step Implementation Plan
Step 1: Copy l1_cache Into l2.sv
Start with a direct copy of the current l1_cache structure.

Keep these pieces:

set/tag/data arrays
valid bits
dirty bits
MSHR arrays
writeback FIFO concept
install-on-resolved-MSHR flow
You are not keeping the L1 request pipeline as-is. You are only reusing the structure.

Keep from L1
logic [BLOCK_SIZE * 8 - 1:0] set_contents [L2_SETS][L2_WAYS];
logic [TAG_SIZE - 1:0] tags [L2_SETS][L2_WAYS];
logic [L2_WAYS-1:0] set_valids [L2_SETS];
logic [L2_WAYS-1:0] set_dirty [L2_SETS];
Change parameters
parameter L2_CAPACITY = 4096;
parameter L2_WAYS     = 4;
parameter NUM_MSHRS   = 4;
Compute geometry from parameters
localparam int L2_SETS     = L2_CAPACITY / (BLOCK_SIZE * L2_WAYS);
localparam int INDEX_BITS  = $clog2(L2_SETS);
localparam int OFFSET_BITS = $clog2(BLOCK_SIZE);
localparam int TAG_SIZE    = PA_WIDTH - INDEX_BITS - OFFSET_BITS;
Important thinking:

L2 is PIPT, so index and tag are both from physical address
no TLB lookup stage exists in L2
that means the L2 request path is simpler than L1
Step 2: Remove L1-Specific Front-End Logic
Delete all L1-only front-end state that depends on virtual addresses and the TLB wait state.

Remove:

start_index
start_tag
trace_vaddr
curr_word_offset
the 2-stage state machine used for TLB/tag timing
store-word update path based on wdata and word offset
L2 works on full blocks from below L1. For v1:

L1 requests ask for a block
L1 writebacks provide a full block
L2 returns a full block
So L2 does not need word writes for the main interface.

Replace with direct physical-address decode
logic [INDEX_BITS-1:0] req_index;
logic [TAG_SIZE-1:0]   req_tag;

assign req_index = l1_req_paddr[OFFSET_BITS +: INDEX_BITS];
assign req_tag   = l1_req_paddr[PA_WIDTH-1 -: TAG_SIZE];
Also create decode for writeback input:

logic [INDEX_BITS-1:0] wb_index_in;
logic [TAG_SIZE-1:0]   wb_tag_in;

assign wb_index_in = l1_wb_paddr[OFFSET_BITS +: INDEX_BITS];
assign wb_tag_in   = l1_wb_paddr[PA_WIDTH-1 -: TAG_SIZE];
Important thinking:

Miss requests and writeback requests are different operations
Do not force them through the same state path at first
Keep them separate in logic
Step 3: Define the L2 Operational Priority
Use a fixed priority order every cycle.

Recommended order:

capture memory response into matching MSHR
install one resolved MSHR into the cache
accept one L1 writeback
process one L1 request
issue one request to memory
This is simple and safe because:

returning data should be consumed first
resolved MSHRs should drain promptly
writebacks should not be dropped
L1 miss requests should still get service
memory issue can be combinational from pending state
Important thinking:

this avoids losing fills
this avoids dropping dirty victims
this makes debugging much easier
Step 4: Implement L1 Writeback Handling First
This is the simplest path to get L2 talking to L1.

Behavior
When l1_wb_valid is high:

look up the block in L2
if it hits:
overwrite the whole line with l1_wb_data
set dirty bit
update LRU
assert l1_wb_ack
if it misses:
choose install way
if victim is dirty, push victim into L2 writeback FIFO to memory
install l1_wb_data
mark valid and dirty
update LRU
assert l1_wb_ack
Hit snippet
if (wb_hit) begin
    set_contents[wb_index_in][wb_hit_way] <= l1_wb_data;
    set_dirty[wb_index_in][wb_hit_way]    <= 1'b1;
    set_valids[wb_index_in][wb_hit_way]   <= 1'b1;
    l1_wb_ack                             <= 1'b1;
end
Miss snippet
if (!wb_hit) begin
    if (victim_dirty) begin
        wb_push       = 1'b1;
        wb_push_paddr = victim_paddr;
        wb_push_data  = victim_data;
    end

    set_contents[wb_index_in][victim_way] <= l1_wb_data;
    tags[wb_index_in][victim_way]         <= wb_tag_in;
    set_valids[wb_index_in][victim_way]   <= 1'b1;
    set_dirty[wb_index_in][victim_way]    <= 1'b1;
    l1_wb_ack                             <= 1'b1;
end
Important thinking:

L1 writeback already contains the full correct block
do not allocate an MSHR for this
treat it like a cache install/update operation
if you do not ack it, L1 will hold the writeback and may stall
Step 5: Implement L1 Miss Request Handling
This is the second major path.

Behavior
When l1_req_valid is high:

decode index/tag from l1_req_paddr
check cache for hit
if hit:
return line immediately on l1_data_valid
if miss:
search all MSHRs for same address
if already outstanding, do not allocate a duplicate MSHR
if not outstanding and free MSHR exists, allocate one
if no MSHR free, just leave the request pending externally; L1 will keep asserting it
Hit response
if (req_hit) begin
    l1_data_valid <= 1'b1;
    l1_data_paddr <= l1_req_paddr;
    l1_data       <= set_contents[req_index][req_hit_way];
end
Miss allocate
if (!req_hit && !mshr_has_same_addr && !mshr_full) begin
    mshr_paddr[mshr_free_idx]      <= l1_req_paddr;
    mshr_state[mshr_free_idx]      <= MS_UNRESOLVED;
    mshr_mem_issued[mshr_free_idx] <= 1'b0;
end
Important thinking:

duplicate miss suppression is important
otherwise repeated L1 requests can waste MSHRs
do not ack or consume anything explicitly here; L1 already uses persistent valid behavior
Step 6: Expand MSHRs to 4 Entries
L2 must support 4 outstanding misses.

Keep the L1 pattern, but extend it.

Suggested MSHR fields
logic [1:0]              mshr_state      [NUM_MSHRS];
logic [PA_WIDTH-1:0]     mshr_paddr      [NUM_MSHRS];
logic                    mshr_mem_issued [NUM_MSHRS];
logic [BLOCK_SIZE*8-1:0] mshr_block      [NUM_MSHRS];
Suggested states
localparam [1:0] MS_IDLE       = 2'b00;
localparam [1:0] MS_UNRESOLVED = 2'b01;
localparam [1:0] MS_WAIT_MEM   = 2'b10;
localparam [1:0] MS_RESOLVED   = 2'b11;
Meaning
MS_IDLE: free
MS_UNRESOLVED: allocated, not yet sent to memory
MS_WAIT_MEM: memory request accepted, waiting for response
MS_RESOLVED: memory returned line, waiting to install
Important thinking:

L1 only needed unresolved/resolved because its lower-level interface was simple
L2 talks to memory with real ready/valid, so issued/not-issued should be explicit
this makes backpressure much easier to reason about
Step 7: Add Memory Request Logic
L2 must send two different things to memory:

read misses
dirty evictions
Use one shared output port with priority.

Memory request priority
dirty writeback FIFO first
then one unissued MSHR read request
Combinational selection
assign mem_req_valid    = !wb_empty || have_mem_read;
assign mem_req_is_write = !wb_empty;
assign mem_req_addr     = !wb_empty ? wb_paddr_q[wb_head] : mshr_paddr[mem_issue_idx];
assign mem_req_wdata    = !wb_empty ? wb_data_q[wb_head]  : '0;
On acceptance
if (mem_req_valid && mem_req_ready) begin
    if (!wb_empty) begin
        wb_pop <= 1'b1;
    end else begin
        mshr_state[mem_issue_idx]      <= MS_WAIT_MEM;
        mshr_mem_issued[mem_issue_idx] <= 1'b1;
    end
end
Important thinking:

always prioritize dirty writebacks to avoid FIFO overflow
this is the simplest arbitration rule
it also prevents silently losing evicted data
Step 8: Match Memory Responses by Address
This should mirror the current L1 behavior.

Response match logic
for (int i = 0; i < NUM_MSHRS; i++) begin
    if (mshr_state[i] == MS_WAIT_MEM &&
        mem_resp_valid &&
        mem_resp_paddr == mshr_paddr[i]) begin
        mshr_block[i] <= mem_resp_rdata;
        mshr_state[i] <= MS_RESOLVED;
    end
end
Important thinking:

this is why mem_resp_paddr is needed
do not assume responses come back in issue order
once you have 4 MSHRs, explicit matching is safer and cleaner
Step 9: Install Resolved MSHRs Into L2
This is the same idea as L1.

When a resolved MSHR is ready:

choose victim way
if victim dirty, queue memory writeback
install returned block
update tag/valid/dirty
update LRU
return block to L1
free the MSHR
Install snippet
set_contents[mshr_index[i]][victim_way] <= mshr_block[i];
tags[mshr_index[i]][victim_way]         <= mshr_paddr[i][PA_WIDTH-1 -: TAG_SIZE];
set_valids[mshr_index[i]][victim_way]   <= 1'b1;
set_dirty[mshr_index[i]][victim_way]    <= 1'b0;

l1_data_valid <= 1'b1;
l1_data_paddr <= mshr_paddr[i];
l1_data       <= mshr_block[i];

mshr_state[i] <= MS_IDLE;
Important thinking:

returning data to L1 should happen when the line is ready
install should happen before freeing the MSHR
if victim is dirty and FIFO is full, do not install yet; retry next cycle
Step 10: Replace 2-Way LRU With 4-Way n^2 LRU
L1 uses a 1-bit LRU because it is 2-way. L2 cannot.

Use an n^2 matrix.

Data structure
logic [L2_WAYS-1:0][L2_WAYS-1:0] lru_matrix [L2_SETS];
Interpretation:

lru_matrix[set][i][j] = 1 means way i is newer than way j
Update on access/install of way k
for (int j = 0; j < L2_WAYS; j++) begin
    if (j != k) begin
        lru_matrix[set][k][j] <= 1'b1;
        lru_matrix[set][j][k] <= 1'b0;
    end
end
lru_matrix[set][k][k] <= 1'b0;
Victim selection
Pick:

any invalid way first
otherwise the way whose row has no 1s against other valid ways
Pseudo-code:

victim_way = invalid_way_if_any;
if (!have_invalid) begin
    for each way i:
        if row i is oldest against all valid ways:
            victim_way = i;
end
Important thinking:

invalid ways always win before LRU
verify LRU with repeated same-set accesses
n^2 LRU is simple to debug even if it uses more bits
Step 11: Keep a Writeback FIFO to Memory
L2 also needs buffering for dirty evictions.

Use the same concept as L1, but make it deeper.

Recommendation
localparam int WB_DEPTH = NUM_MSHRS;
Reason:

multiple MSHRs may resolve close together
each install may evict a dirty victim
without a queue, one writeback can overwrite another
Important thinking:

do not use a single writeback register
a queue is safer and matches the current L1 cleanup direction
Step 12: Update memsys.sv
Once l2.sv exists, wire it into the actual top level.

Add L2 instance
Use the current L1 wires already present:

logic                       l1_l2_wb_valid;
logic [PA_WIDTH-1:0]        l1_l2_wb_paddr;
logic [BLOCK_SIZE*8-1:0]    l1_l2_wb_data;
logic                       l2_l1_wb_ack;
logic                       l1_l2_req_valid;
logic [PA_WIDTH-1:0]        l1_l2_req_paddr;
logic                       l2_l1_data_valid;
logic [PA_WIDTH-1:0]        l2_l1_data_paddr;
logic [BLOCK_SIZE*8-1:0]    l2_l1_data;
Memory response needs one extra wire
input logic [PA_WIDTH-1:0] mem_resp_paddr,
Connect the module
l2_cache #(
    .L2_CAPACITY (L2_CAPACITY),
    .L2_WAYS     (L2_WAYS),
    .BLOCK_SIZE  (BLOCK_SIZE),
    .NUM_MSHRS   (L2_MSHRS),
    .PA_WIDTH    (PA_WIDTH),
    .DATA_WIDTH  (DATA_WIDTH)
) u_l2 (
    .clk          (clk),
    .rst_n        (rst_n),

    .l1_wb_valid  (l1_l2_wb_valid),
    .l1_wb_paddr  (l1_l2_wb_paddr),
    .l1_wb_data   (l1_l2_wb_data),
    .l1_wb_ack    (l2_l1_wb_ack),

    .l1_req_valid (l1_l2_req_valid),
    .l1_req_paddr (l1_l2_req_paddr),

    .l1_data_valid(l2_l1_data_valid),
    .l1_data_paddr(l2_l1_data_paddr),
    .l1_data      (l2_l1_data),

    .mem_req_valid(mem_req_valid),
    .mem_req_is_write(mem_req_is_write),
    .mem_req_addr (mem_req_addr),
    .mem_req_wdata(mem_req_wdata),
    .mem_req_ready(mem_req_ready),

    .mem_resp_valid(mem_resp_valid),
    .mem_resp_paddr(mem_resp_paddr),
    .mem_resp_rdata(mem_resp_rdata)
);
Important thinking:

do not redesign all of memsys.sv
only add the missing memory response address wire and the new L2 instance
keep the rest stable while debugging L2
Recommended Build Order
Follow this exact order.

Create l2.sv from l1_cache.sv
Strip TLB/VA-specific logic
Add new L2 ports
Implement hit/miss lookup for l1_req_valid
Implement writeback accept/update path for l1_wb_valid
Add 4-entry MSHR allocation and response matching
Add memory request issue logic
Add install-from-resolved-MSHR logic
Replace LRU with 4-way n^2 LRU
Add/resize L2 writeback FIFO
Wire L2 into memsys.sv
Write and run a dedicated tb_l2_accurate.sv
This order matters because:

connectivity bugs are easier to debug before replacement bugs
miss/fill protocol bugs are easier to debug before LRU bugs
LRU is easier to test once fills and evictions already work
What to Watch Out For
1. Duplicate MSHR allocation
If l1_req_valid stays high for the same miss, you must not allocate multiple MSHRs for the same block.

2. Dirty victim loss
If two resolved MSHRs both evict dirty blocks close together, a single writeback register will lose data. Use a queue.

3. Wrong memory response match
If memory response matching is not by address, returned blocks may install into the wrong MSHR.

4. Wrong LRU victim
n^2 LRU update bugs are easy to make. Always test repeated accesses in one set and check the chosen victim explicitly.

5. Missing backpressure behavior
If memory is not ready, do not mark an MSHR as issued and do not pop a writeback.

6. Returning data before install state is valid
Return data to L1 only when the block is fully available and associated with the correct address.

Suggested Tests
Write tb_l2_accurate.sv after the module skeleton is in place.

Connectivity tests
reset clears arrays, MSHRs, FIFO
L1 writeback hit updates line
L1 writeback miss installs line and acks
L1 read hit returns correct line
L1 miss allocates one MSHR
memory response resolves matching MSHR
Behavior tests
two different misses occupy two MSHRs
same miss does not allocate duplicate MSHR
dirty victim creates memory writeback
back-to-back dirty victims both survive in FIFO
4-way same-set accesses exercise n^2 LRU
invalid way chosen before LRU way
wrong-address memory response ignored
Final Notes
This is the simplest practical way to build L2 from the current codebase:

copy L1 structure
remove TLB/VA-specific front-end
connect L1 miss and writeback wires first
connect memory wires second
add 4-entry MSHRs
add 4-way n^2 LRU
test connectivity before policy
If you follow the build order above, you can debug one subsystem at a time instead of trying to solve protocol, MSHR, and replacement bugs all at once.

